For the first two orientations, there is only one way to place another piece to cover the lower left corner. In the last orientation, it is impossible to cover the lower left corner without overlapping the first piece. This insight allows us to break down the problem into smaller subproblems.
1. Consider the three different ways an L-shaped piece can cover the top left unit square of the board.

2. For the first two orientations, observe that there is only one way to place another piece to cover the lower left corner. In both cases, the two leftmost columns will be covered.

3. For the last orientation, note that it is impossible to cover the lower left corner without overlapping the first piece.

4. Apply the same logic to the remaining uncovered top left square, as the two leftmost columns are now covered.

5. Observe that there are two choices for covering the first two columns, two choices for covering the next two columns, and two choices for covering the last two columns.

6. Calculate the total number of ways to cover the entire board by multiplying the number of choices for each pair of columns: $2 \times 2 \times 2 = 8$.

The given solution demonstrates how to perform long division in base 4, which is similar to the process in base 10. The key insight is to recognize that the digits and arithmetic operations follow the rules of base 4 instead of base 10.
1. Set up the long division in base 4:
   $$
   \begin{array}{cc|cccc}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & & & \\
   \cline{3-6}
   1 & 1 & 1 & 0 & 2 & 3 \\
