The key insight in this problem is to recognize that the four distinct positive integers less than $8$ that are invertible modulo $8$ are $1$, $3$, $5$, and $7$. Additionally, each of these numbers is its own inverse modulo $8$. This property allows for a simplification of the expression $(abc+abd+acd+bcd)(abcd)^{-1}$.
1. Identify the four distinct positive integers less than $8$ that are invertible modulo $8$: $1$, $3$, $5$, and $7$.

2. Expand the expression $(abc+abd+acd+bcd)(abcd)^{-1}$:
$$\begin{align*}
(abc+abd+acd+bcd)(abcd)^{-1} &= abc(abcd)^{-1} + abd(abcd)^{-1} + acd(abcd)^{-1} + bcd(abcd)^{-1} \\
&= a^{-1} + b^{-1} + c^{-1} + d^{-1}
\end{align*}$$

3. Observe that each of the four numbers ($1$, $3$, $5$, and $7$) is its own inverse modulo $8$:
$$\begin{align*}
1^{-1} &\equiv 1 \pmod{8} \\
3^{-1} &\equiv 3 \pmod{8} \\
5^{-1} &\equiv 5 \pmod{8} \\
7^{-1} &\equiv 7 \pmod{8}
\end{align*}$$

4. Substitute the values and calculate the sum modulo $8$:
$$\begin{align*}
a^{-1} + b^{-1} + c^{-1} + d^{-1} &\equiv 1 + 3 + 5 + 7 \pmod{8} \\
&\equiv 16 \pmod{8} \\
&\equiv 0 \pmod{8}
\end{align*}$$

The approach taken in this solution is based on the concept of direct proportion. When two quantities are directly proportional, their ratios are equal. By setting up a proportion using the known cost and number of roses in one bouquet, we can solve for the cost of a bouquet with a different number of roses. This approach is effective because it allows us to find the missing value (cost) by comparing the ratios of the known quantities (number of roses and cost).
Let $c$ equal the cost of a bouquet of 39 roses (in dollars). Since we know that the price of a bouquet is directly proportional to the number of roses it contains, we can set up the following proportion $$\begin{align*} \frac{c}{39}&=\frac{20}{12}
\\\Rightarrow \qquad c&=\left(\frac{20}{12}\right)(39)
\\\Rightarrow \qquad c&=\boxed{65}
\end{align*}$$
A bouquet containing 39 roses will cost $\boxed{\$65}$ at Rosa's Rose Shop.
